The article is a transcript of a briefing by Secretary Clinton, Secretary Gates, and Admiral Mullen on the announcement of the new START treaty. The treaty aims to reduce the number of strategic nuclear weapons that the United States and Russia are permitted to deploy by a third, and maintains an effective verification regime. The treaty also demonstrates the commitment of both countries to strengthen the global non-proliferation regime and keep nuclear materials out of the wrong hands. The briefing emphasizes the importance of trust, transparency, and cooperation between the United States and Russia in reducing the threat posed by nuclear weapons. The article also addresses concerns about missile defense and the future of nuclear disarmament. Secretary Clinton expresses confidence in the ratification of the treaty by the Senate, highlighting the bipartisan support that past nuclear arms treaties have received. The briefing concludes with a discussion on the implications of the treaty for Iran and the Middle East.